          <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold mb-3">A Kanban board across the whole session fleet</h3>
          <p class="text-[var(--color-fg-muted)] leading-relaxed text-sm">
            Four columns — Queued, Running, Blocked, Done — derived entirely from
            data the platform already tracks: a session's <code class="font-mono text-sm">status</code>
            plus its most recent event's <code class="font-mono text-sm">stop_reason</code>.
            No new backend state, no separate "board" resource — an idle session
            with no events yet reads as queued, one whose last event is
            <code class="font-mono text-sm">session.status_idle</code> with
            <code class="font-mono text-sm">stop_reason.type === "requires_action"</code>
            reads as blocked (waiting on a tool confirmation), everything else
            idle reads as done. Polls every 15s — useful the moment you're
            running more sessions than fit in one browser tab, e.g. the
            self-improvement-agent triaging a backlog of issues concurrently.
